  "success": true,
  "message": "Message sent to team-lead's inbox",
  "routing": {
    "sender": "kantian-expert",
    "senderColor": "pink",
    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Yes to both notes, with one caveat",
    "content": "**Yes, both notes.** Brief reasoning:\n\nAt line 17, the author already provides a gloss: 境界（界限）. The reader is being given a definition *by the author*. A brief TN here (\"境界, literally 'boundary of Jing (境)'; the author glosses it as 界限, 'limit'\") rides the author's own pedagogical moment -- it costs almost nothing in reader attention because the author is already pausing to explain.\n\nIf we skip line 17 and only note line 25, the reader encounters 境界 three times without knowing it contains 境. By the time they reach the deeper footnote at line 25, the connection arrives too late to have shaped their reading of lines 17-19. The whole foreword section is about the *limits of thought* (境界) as the motivation for studying the *structure of thought* (境) -- if the reader does not see the 境 inside 境界 from the start, they miss that the concept of 境 *emerges from* the concept of boundary.\n\n**Caveat:** The line 17 note must be very brief -- one sentence, etymological only. Save the philosophical weight for line 25. Two heavy notes in eight lines would overburden the reader.\n"
  }
}
